abstract: The Clinton and Obama campaigns are aggressively pursuing members of a group that could decide the outcome at the convention.
snippet: The Clinton and Obama campaigns are aggressively pursuing members of a group that could decide the outcome at the convention.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON  Seeing a good possibility that the Democratic presidential nomination will not be settled in the primaries and caucuses, Senators Hillary Rodham Clinton and Barack Obama are lavishing attention on a group that might hold the balance of power: elected officials and party leaders who could decide the outcome at the convention in August.

abstract: Rachel K. Paulose, the United States attorney in Minnesota, said that she would step down to go to work at the Justice Department in Washington on legal policies.
snippet: Rachel K. Paulose, the United States attorney in Minnesota, said that she would step down to go to work at the Justice Department in Washington on legal policies.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON, Nov. 19 — The embattled United States attorney in Minnesota announced on Monday that she would step down to go to work at the Justice Department in Washington on legal policies.

abstract: Senator Hillary Rodham Clinton, along with 29 other Democratic senators, signed a letter to President Bush expressing “serious concerns” about the administration’s posture toward Iran.
snippet: Senator Hillary Rodham Clinton, along with 29 other Democratic senators, signed a letter to President Bush expressing “serious concerns” about the administration’s posture toward Iran.
lead_paragraph: Hillary Rodham Clinton’s Senate office announced this afternoon that Mrs. Clinton, along with 29 other Democratic senators, had signed a letter to President Bush expressing “serious concerns” about the administration’s posture toward Iran and its strategy to stop that nation from developing nuclear weapons.

abstract: WASHINGTON — The chief executive of Mattel apologized Wednesday to Congress for failing to stop lead-laced toys from entering the global marketplace, vowing to take immediate steps to join with others in the toy industry to prevent it from happening again.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The chief executive of Mattel apologized Wednesday to Congress for failing to stop lead-laced toys from entering the global marketplace, vowing to take immediate steps to join with others in the toy industry to prevent it from happening again.
